{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01SrvePwv9TQxQj7kMp93TE3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to generate 10 realistic fake OCR recipe text files. Let me understand the requirements:\n\n1. Save to `tools/title-loop/input/{RECIPE_TITLE}.generated.24.txt`\n2. Filename rules:\n   - Use SPACES, not hyphens or underscores\n   - Preserve Polish diacritics (e.g., \"Żurek.generated.24.txt\")\n   - Filename title must match the main title in content\n3. Recipe mix: ~60% English, ~40% Polish\n4. Variety of categories and title lengths\n5. Different from the existing list\n6. Pattern requirements:\n   - 5 files with SPLIT_TITLE (title across 2-4 lines)\n   - 3 files with METADATA_PREFIX (category/serving info before title)\n   - 2 files with OCR_CORRUPTION (misrecognized characters)\n7. File length: 15-60 lines\n\nLet me create 10 unique recipes that aren't in the excluded list:\n\nEnglish recipes:\n1. Crispy Chicken Thighs - SPLIT_TITLE\n2. Roasted Brussels Sprouts - METADATA_PREFIX\n3. Lemon Garlic Pasta - OCR_CORRUPTION\n4. Beef Bourguignon - SPLIT_TITLE\n5. Butternut Squash Soup - METADATA_PREFIX\n6. Baked Cod with Herbs - standard\n7. Vanilla Panna Cotta - standard\n\nPolish recipes:\n8. Piernik z Malinami - SPLIT_TITLE\n9. Żurek z Żytem - METADATA_PREFIX\n10. Bigos Wiosenny - OCR_CORRUPTION\n\nLet me distribute the patterns:\n- SPLIT_TITLE (5): Crispy Chicken Thighs, Beef Bourguignon, Piernik z Malinami, (need 2 more)\n\n\n- METADATA_PREFIX (3): Roasted Brussels Sprouts, Butternut Squash Soup, Żurek z Żytem\n- OCR_CORRUPTION (2): Lemon Garlic Pasta, Bigos Wiosenny\n\nI need two more recipes for SPLIT_TITLE. I'll add Grilled Halibut with Rosemary and Sernik z Czarnuszką to round out the patterns. For the remaining slots, I can use Chrupiące Roladki and Mushroom Risotto as standard format recipes. uszką as standard. That gives me 11 total, but I need exactly 10. Removing Sernik z Czarnuszką brings me to the right count with the distribution I need: 4 SPLIT_TITLE files, 3 METADATA_PREFIX, 2 OCR_CORRUPTION, and 1 standard. Actually, I realize I need 5 SPLIT_TITLE entries, not 4, so I should reassign some of the other categories to hit the correct breakdown.\n\nLet me reorganize: Crispy Chicken Thighs and Beef Bourguignon as SPLIT_TITLE, Roasted Brussels Sprouts and Butternut Squash Soup as METADATA_PREFIX, Lemon Garlic Pasta and Bigos Wiosenny as OCR_CORRUPTION, then Chrupiące Roladki, Żurek z Żytem, Mushroom and Barley Risotto, and Grilled Halibut with Rosemary as the remaining SPLIT_TITLE entries. That gives me 5 SPLIT_TITLE, 3 METADATA_PREFIX, 2 OCR_CORRUPTION—exactly what I need. Now I'll generate each file with appropriate OCR issues: the SPLIT_TITLE ones will have titles broken across lines, METADATA_PREFIX files will have category headers, and OCR_CORRUPTION entries will contain garbled text. 4 | 20 minutes prep | 35 minutes cooking\n\nIngredients:\n4 bone-in, skin-on chicken thighs\n2 tablespoons salt\n1 tablespoon black pepper\n1 tablespoon paprika\n2 cloves garlic, minced\n2 tablespoons olive oil\nFresh thyme for garnish\n\nMethod:\n1. Preheat oven to 400°F (200°C)\n2. Pat chicken thighs dry with paper towels\n3. In a small bowl, combine salt, pepper, paprika, and garlic\n4. Rub the spice mixture all over the chicken thighs\n5. Heat olive oil in a cast-iron skillet over medium-high heat\n6. Place chicken thighs skin-side down and sear for 6-8 minutes until skin is golden and crispy\n7.\n\nFlip and sear the other side for 3-4 minutes. Transfer the skillet to the preheated oven and bake for 20-25 minutes until the internal temperature reaches 165°F (74°C). Let rest for 5 minutes before garnishing with fresh thyme and serving alongside roasted vegetables.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":87958,"cache_read_input_tokens":15568,"cache_creation":{"e